description:
## Severity
Minor
## Dimension
error-handling
## Location
src/plugins/mod.rs:399-460, src/plugins/mod.rs:542-613, src/plugins/mod.rs:781-819
## Violation
The component resolvers drop every read / parse failure into the void using `if let Ok(...)` chains with no else branch. resolved_commands silently `unwrap_or_default()` on file content. Quoted lines:

    if let Ok(content) = fs::read_to_string(&mcp_json) {
        if let Ok(wrapper) =
            serde_json::from_str::<HashMap<String, serde_json::Value>>(&content)
        {
            ...
            if let Ok(servers) = serde_json::from_str::<HashMap<String, McpServerConfig>>(&content) {
                self.mcp_configs.extend(servers);
            }
        }
    }
    ...
    let raw_content = fs::read_to_string(path).unwrap_or_default();
    let front_matter = parse_command_front_matter(&raw_content);

A plugin author who shipped a broken .mcp.json or hooks.json gets no diagnostic — the plugin loads with the broken component silently absent. Operators chasing "why doesn't my MCP server start?" have no signal to grep for. The Plugin::load contract is `Result<Self, PluginError>` but it returns Ok even when half the plugin failed to parse.
## Mandated refactor
Each resolver should accumulate `Vec<PluginError>` in the Plugin (or a `warnings: Vec<String>` field) and surface them via a new `Plugin::warnings()` accessor. Replace `unwrap_or_default()` with `.context()` -> `warn!(error = %e, "Plugin command file unreadable")` so operators see the failure in tracing logs. The CLI's `/plugin validate` should print accumulated warnings under a "Warnings" header next to "PASSED".
## Filed from QA review dispatch
